  "summary": "A 1919 Yiddish socialist parody Haggadah presented in a 2025 bilingual edition. Its English translation preserves a forceful labor voice and inventive ritual reinterpretations, while the translator explicitly warns about racist progress narratives, anti-religious simplification, and glorification of revolutionary violence. It belongs only in an opt-in historical secular or labor path with the warning attached.",
  "sourceAssessment": {
    "voice": "Satirical, polemical, secular, Yiddish-inflected, class-conscious, and deliberately modeled on traditional Haggadah formulas.",
    "bestUses": [
      "Historical labor and secular Jewish context",
      "A class-conscious Four Questions adaptation",
      "Readings on work, hunger, housing, dignity, and collective freedom",
      "Long adult Seders explicitly choosing socialist or labor history"
    ],
    "beginnerRisks": [
      "The text is a historical polemic, not a neutral account of socialism, religion, labor history, or Jewish tradition.",
      "Its Yiddish-English page pattern means coherent English sequences skip intervening Yiddish counterparts while preserving source order.",
      "The original contains racist theories of historical progress, anti-Christian and anti-religious attacks, hostile class labels, and endorsements of violent revolution.",
      "Transliterated liturgical phrases and period idiom need definitions for readers who do not know Yiddish or Hebrew."
    ],
    "politicalContext": "Treat every recommended sequence as an explicitly selected historical labor document. Preserve the translator's 2025 warning before any excerpt; never present violent revolution, contempt for religion, demeaning class labels, or pseudo-evolutionary claims as the app's own position. The source contains no basis for blaming contemporary religious, ethnic, national, or economic groups collectively.",
    "creditContext": "Credit Benjamin Feigenbaum, Leon Zolotkof, Shlomo Jack Enkin Lewis, Hagode Shel Peysekh: In a Socialist Mode, and the 2025 translation on the final sources page. Indicate that the original is public domain and the translation is Attribution-ShareAlike, preserving notices about changes."
  },
